SGB President-Elect Julie Crowell agreed
with Pasquale on the accomplishments of the
board.

“This year’s board has been exceptional,”

said Crowell. “We’ve changed this office

into an office that can be taken seriously.”
Crowell said her task as next year’s presi-

dent will be difficult without her comrades

on this year’s board but feels hopeful about‘

next year.

“I am hopeful to work with the new board
members and try to live up to, and even suc-
ceed, this year’s board,” said Crowell.

Among the student issues to which Crowell
said she plans to attend next year is the
establishment of a better dialogue with the
university community and with student
groups.

“We’1l be doing a lot of experimentation to
reach out to as many students,” she said.
“We will engage in more publicity for our
meetings and open forums.”

