Placement center helps stuclents lincl jobs

By Mark Gordon
and John B. Moore
The Pitt News

Diploma in hand, a mass of graduating
seniors prepares to step out into the post-co1-
lege world and battle the unexpected while
looking for employment. But with the help
of the University Placement Center, students
no longer have to face the responsibility
alone.

Located on the second ﬂoor of the William
Pitt Union, the placement center offers job-
hunting skills, advice and counselling and
matches students with prospective recruiters.

While it has been around for nearly 50
years, the most drastic changes have taken
place in the last four or ﬁve years, according
to Placement Center Director Bob Perkoski.

‘The marketplace has changed,” Perkoski
said. “How people get hired is not the
same.”

According to Perkoski, companies are
much more diverse today in their hiring
practices. That is where the Placement
Center comes in.

Perkoski said that if a prospective employ-
er would call him on a Monday, by Tuesday
the employer would have the resumes of Pitt
students that match the company’s needs.

One goal of Perkoski’s is to make Pitt stu-
dents more competitive in the job market.

“Because you’re competing against other
schools, you’re competing against a whole
myriad of factors,” Perkoski said. “You
become competitive by knowing how com-
panies hire,” Perkoski said.

He said the counselors, or “portfolio man-
agers,” at the placement center are trained in
marketing, in knowing companies’ hiring
policies. The counselors are also responsible
for training students on resume writing and
then matching up students with jobs.

“This is not a one—contact ofﬁce where

you walk in, make one contact and then go
home,” Perkoski said.

The center has been very successful in
finding jobs for students, according to
Perkoski.

“We’ve done well,” he said. “Last year
35% of the people that did ﬁnd jobs found
them as a result of our direct services.”

Perkoski said new computer systems have
given the placement service an opportunity
to respond to a business inquiry in one day.

He said that one of the systems is called
Alum-Net, a computerized program that
helps students get in contact with Pitt alum-

ni. There is also a resume referral system __

that was developed to connect prospective
employers with graduating seniors in a mini-
mal amount of time.

“We’re trying to be more sensitive to com-
panies and their needs,” Perkoski said.
“We’re also trying to be more sensitive to
students and what they want.”

