Newt on welfare

Now that the Republicans have control of both houses of
Congress, welfare reform has become a viable issue again. There
are few who would dispute the need for some sort of welfare
reform. However, there are even fewer people who can actually
agree on a plan for reform.

Speaker of the House-in-waiting Newt Gingrich has his plan,
of course, and it has been getting a great deal of criticism recent-
ly. Gingrich supports a proposal which would ban states from
paying welfare benefits to children whose paternity is not estab-
lished and to those born out of wedlock under 18. The money
saved would then be used to establish orphanages and group
homes for unwed mothers and to promote adoption.

Gingrich argues that this is preferable to the present system,
which is “allowing the brutalization of children in this country.”
He claimed that there were over 800 cases of child abandomnent
is Washington, D.C. alone last year. Gingrich furthermore desires
the implementation of an 800 number which women could call
who desire to give up their children.

Gingrich’s program has been criticized from many sources.
Hillary Clinton called the program “unbelievable and absurd,”
and other critics have assailed the program as expensive.

While we agree that welfare refonn is desperately needed in
this country, we question Gingrich’s plarmed solution. First of all,
it really does nothing to address the problems of welfare. What is

the difference between cutting benefits to women under 18 com- -

pared to those who are, say, 22? The same socioeconomic prob-
lems occur regardless of age and may very likely be more pro-
nounced at a younger age. To isolate a particular age group is not
a solution to welfare, but rather sounds like Gingrich trying to
enforce his view of how society should be. It strikes us as just
more Christian “family values” talk and the legislation of morali-
ty.

Furthermore, welfare reform needs to be comprehensive. Even
if Gingrich’s program of eliminating beneﬁts is viable, which it
may be, it must be applied across the board. To target only cer-
tain groups with a speciﬁc plan will not solve the problem and
will only create more bureaucracy. Congress needs to work
towards developing a bipartisan comprehensive plan for welfare
reform. Despite their majorities, the Republicans do not have
enough votes to force through welfare reform. However,
Gingrich, who would likely formulate or play a signiﬁcant role in

. formulating a House plan, is far from acting in a manner which is

conducive to compromise. He has made other outrageous claims
such as claiming that a quarter of the White House staff use
drugs and has been vocal on his plans for a Bosnian solution.

Although some of his proposals are certainly viable or possible
solutions to problems facing the nation, Gingrich must remember
that he is not the president and is also not an enraged outsider.
Gingrich has reached the middle of the Washington power circle
and needs to stop playing politics and instead start trying to lead
the House of Representatives.

